b Rhesus antibodies can only be detected with laboratory screening and identification techniques that are complex to implement.
}

\section*{If Rhesus D identical blood is not available:}

\section*{Rh D negative blood to Rh D positive recipients}

Rh D negative blood may be transfused to Rh D positive recipients without immunological consequences, but only as second choice, since Rh D negative blood is rare and should be kept for Rh D negative recipients.

\section*{Rh D positive blood to Rh D negative recipients}

Under exceptional circumstances (absolute emergency), Rh D positive blood may be transfused to Rh D negative recipients:
- There will be no immediate transfusion reaction in Rh D negative men and nulliparous women who have never been transfused.
- Incompatibility reactions may occur if the recipient has developed acquired anti-D antibodies through previous transfusion or pregnancy. Since the simple crossmatch method cannot detect anti-D antibodies in the recipient, the risk of immediate transfusion reaction and ineffective transfusion is unpredictable.

Therefore, the decision to transfuse Rh D positive blood to Rh D negative patients must be a well-considered medical decision, taking into account not only the immediate risks but also the potential consequences:
1. The recipient has a high likelihood ( $80 \%$ risk) of developing anti-D antibodies after a transfusion with an incompatible Rh D blood unit: any future transfusions with Rh D positive blood may cause adverse events.
2. Rh D negative women are likely to experience obstetrical complications if they subsequently conceive Rh D positive children.

