\section*{If screening is performed before donation:}
- Draw a blood sample in an EDTA ${ }^{\text {a }}$ tube.
- Perform the first blood grouping, the first HIV test ${ }^{\text {b }}$, and the test for hepatitis B, C and syphilis ${ }^{\text {c }}$ on the EDTA tube.
- Exclude the donor if any of the TTI test result is positive or doubtful.
- If all TTI tests are clearly negative: collect the blood donation, and then perform the second blood grouping and the second HIV test ${ }^{\mathrm{d}}$ on the blood in the distal segment of the bag tubing.

\section*{If screening is performed after donation:}
- Collect the blood donation.
- At the end of collection, fill an EDTA tube, or in the event of a blood bag with a diversion pouch (sampling arm), fill the EDTA tube as soon as the diversion pouch is full.
- Perform the first blood grouping, the first HIV test and the tests for hepatitis B, C and syphilis using the EDTA tube one by one or in batches ${ }^{\mathrm{e}}$.
- Discard the blood donation if any of the TTI test result is positive or doubtful.
- If all TTI tests are clearly negative, perform the second blood grouping and the 2nd HIV test on the blood of the distal segment of the bag tubing.

In both cases:
If the second HIV test is clearly negative: the blood donation is qualified.
If the second HIV test is positive or doubtful: the blood donation is excluded.
All blood donations with any positive or doubtful test results must be discarded (Chapter 4, Section 7).

