\section*{Description}

In a refrigerator for blood storage, the temperature data logger Fridge-tag ${ }^{\circledR}$ 2, with an external sensor placed in a glycol vial, displays the inside temperature of the refrigerator without opening the door and records temperatures over the last 30 days. A visual alarm flashes when the temperature falls outside the set range.
The sensor placed in a leak-proof vial of glycol records the temperature of a viscous liquid similar to blood. The measured temperature is therefore insensitive to the short temperature variations of the air when opening the fridge door.

\section*{Installation}
1. Activation and setting of date, time and temperature in ${ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ format. This is done by the local logistician or biomed engineer.
2. Pre-set of the duration of lower and upper alarms limits to 15 minutes: the alarm will activate only after 15 minutes outside the desired temperature range.
3. Pre-set of the temperature alarm trigger:
a. Lower alarm : $+2^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
b. Upper alarm : $+6^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
4. Connect the cable to the reader.
5. Fix the reader on the wall behind the refrigerator for a chest refrigerator, or on the side of a vertical blood refrigerator, at eye level for easy reading.
The reader should be removable in order to be able to download the 30 last day temperatures using the USB cable located at the top of the reader.

\section*{Use}

Place the glycol vial with the sensor inside the blood refrigerator at upper basket level, either between cooled blood bags, or hung between the upper baskets.

\section*{Remarks}
- Ensure the glycol vial is not in contact with any freshly collected blood (which is not yet fully refrigerated) or the refrigerator sides or is not close to the bottom of the refrigerator.
- The temperature displayed by the Fridge-tag ${ }^{®} 2$ reader may be different from that displayed at the front bottom right of the refrigerator by up to $1^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. The built-in sensor of the MB 3000 G is located lower and close to the wall of the refrigerator and displays a "calculated" temperature, not the real temperature inside the refrigerator. Take into account the temperature displayed by the Fridge-tag ${ }^{\circledR} 2$.

